3.20.25  2:15 am   i'm learning the guitar. do you think it's just a matter of time and practice before i can play ehat i think/what i hear?

     yes but don't forget to have fun

      my left hand feels so clumsy when switching chords and my index finger stretches outwards when my pinky presses down and i don't know if that shouldn't happen. i feel like i don't know where exactly to learn the basics of "harmony."

     right there, in your own life, in your own experience, with your favorite instrument(s)

     it feels like constructing chords requires some knowledge of harmony amd music terminology that i don't really know.

     fine, but it really won't work right unless you discover it actually YOURself, with YOUR emotions. Everyone on earth who's ever tried to 'explain' how music and harmony works has essentially explained it wrong, and effectively you will too, in a new way not quite like anyone else's. that's why you have to find this yourself. then later you can make friends with all the other people who found similar things but slightly different

      i want to make music. i have come up with and recorded little melodies i thought of, but how do i do that with... chords?

     i'd say if you are in '1 note at a time' mode, just start playing around with maybe SOMETIMES allowing 2 notes. for example if you have a melody, find just ONE note in the melody that can have a helper note with it at the exact same time

     also, chord melody is a concern for me. if i want to play chord melodies, is it the same as playing the chords of a scale based on the intervals between the notes?

     absolutely not

     HARMONY IS CONFUSING!

     so is speaking, and making coherent word sounds with your tongue and mouth shape. i bet you would never be able to explain how you do that. and yet, somehow, after years of fumbling around, you've got it now and it's totally natural to you

     i get the magic of harmony, adding notes on top of notes and all, but i have no idea where to start or how to improve.

     yes i think i'd recommend the above approach, to harmonize just 1 melody note with one other note, at just one moment of your favorite song melody

      also constructing chords or harmonies on guitar isn't as intuitive as piano. or is it?

     harder in some ways, easier in other ways

     i just want to play the beautifully rich sounds i hear in like Chick Corea's and Stevie Wonders' stuff, or in McCoy Tyner's, or Barney Kessel's work too... please help me, give me some direction. i know you're more piano-and-drums-and-bass, but please help! i hope i have explained my problem to you sufficiently

     just like learning a language, the bad news is it takes a long time, the great news is that if you actually are enjoying yourself enough to stay in the game for long enough, there is literally no stopping you from being just as good as any of your favorite names. but you're gonna have to taste the food for yourself, one bite at a time
